To determine the average grain size from the SEM images, the Mean Linear Intercept (MLI) method was employed. For accurate measurement, the SEM image must include a clear scale bar and exhibit well-defined, etched grain boundaries. A series of randomly oriented straight lines is overlaid onto the image. A sufficient number of lines should be drawn to ensure statistical reliability, such that the total test length - adjusted for magnification - spans hundreds of grains. Each intersection between a line and a grain boundary is counted as one intercept. If a line terminates within a grain without crossing a boundary, it is counted as a half intercept. The total number of intercepts is denoted as X. The MLI is then calculated using the standard formula31.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
